<DOC><DOCNO> AP881204-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-88 2309EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-SouthKorea-Cabinet     12-04 0262</FIRST><SECOND>AM-South Korea-Cabinet,0273</SECOND><HEAD>Roh Moves Against Predecessor's Legacy in Cabinet Reshuffle</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Roh Tae-woo carried out abroad cabinet shakeup Monday to sweep away the tainted legacy offormer President Chun Doo-hwan, who went into retreat afterapologizing for abuses during his regime.   Roh named as his new premier Kang Young-hoon, a U.S.-educatedlawmaker in the governing party. Kang replaces Lee Hyun-jae.   The president promised last month to remove the vestiges of theChun Cabinet to help sooth public anger over Chun's authoritarianrule.   Chun stepped down as president last February. On Nov. 23, he wentinto self-imposed internal exile after publicly apologizing forcorruption and repression during his seven-year rule. He has deniedpersonal wrongdoing, however.   Roh replaced all but three posts in the 23-member Cabinet.   Kang, 66, a lawmaker of the governing Democratic Justice Party,was forced to retire as superintendent of the Korean MilitaryAcademy in 1961 when he opposed Park Chung-hee, who ousted thecivilian government in a military coup.   He later went to the United States and earned a doctorate inpolitical science at Southern California University. He served asambassador to Britain and the Holy See in the early 1980s.   Cho Soon, a 60-year-old U.S.-educated economist, was made deputyprime minister and also economic plannmg minister to replace RhaWoong-bae.   The president also named ambassador to Saudi Arabia, 58-year-oldChoi Ho-joong, as the new foreign minister. He succeeds ChoiKwang-soo.   Retired Gen. Lee Sang-hoon became defense minister. He was vicecommander of the Korea-U.S. Combined Forces in 1985 before retiring.</TEXT></DOC>